Your trouble is that you're looking at it the wrong way.  There aren't five correct answers to a category; there are five POSSIBLE answers.  Sometimes, six even.  The job at that point is to look at those five or six and see which one can go into another group.  If you can't, then you just find other groups until you wind up with one of your original five (or two of your original six) in another category.

(I assume "including hole" was a typo, but I have no idea what you meant.)

@Barry Ancona 
per OED, n-less "restaurateur" dates to 1793, one-n "restauranteur" to 1836. Thackeray favored the first, Disraeli the latter, so perhaps is a (French-lovin') Liberal vs. Tory thing. By mid-1860's lazy New Yorkers were using "restauranter." 

It's worthy to note that "restaurateur," and for that matter "restaurant" (in the sense of dining establishment) in both English and French, date to the times of the French Revolution, when so many chefs once employed in noble households needed to find employment elsewhere. For a few sous, you, too, could diner like a duc!

